**Microservices Architecture: Introduction**

Microservices architecture, or simply microservices, has become very popular on the last few years.

I will be writing about microservices on the next articles, and for start I&#39;d like to introduce the concept and present it&#39;s main characteristics.

Microservice architecture is a very complex subject and this article was written with the intent to be very brief and introductory, without complex issues...however, I will be composing more specific articles in a near future.

**Monolithic**

First of all, lets talk about the opposite way of implementing an application, the monolithic way:

- Different from microservices, a monolithic application is built as a single, self contained, and autonomous unit. For instance, in a server/client model, the monolithic  application is the back-end that handles requests, perform logic and accesses the persistence layer.
- Any changes made on a small section of the application, most of the times, requires building, and deploying a new version of the entire application, instead of just deploying that small section separately, without affecting the clients.
- A big team may be required to maintain every aspect of the application.
- If it is necessary to scale a single feature of the application, probably it will be necessary to scale the entire application into new server nodes, consuming a lot unnecessary machine resources just to maintain that single feature alive and running smoothly.

But not everything is lost, microservices are here to save us !

**Microservices Way**

Basically, in simple words, a microservice is a small component that provides specific context features, communicate using standard protocols, and when combined with other microservices it forms one or more applications.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Systems built as microservices are decomposed into multiple component services, so that each of these units can be deployed, modified, and then re-deployed independently without compromising the system&#39;s health.  As a result, you might only need to change one or more distinct services instead of having to redeploy entire applications.  But this approach does have its downsides, including expensive remote calls and increased complexity when redistributing responsibilities between components.

On microservices style &quot;you build it, you run it&quot; ! A component service may be sustained by a single small team, that is responsible of maintaining and developing it&#39;s features. Unlike a traditional monolithic development approach, where different teams each have a specific focus on(eg.: UIs, databases, technology layers, or server-side logic), microservice architecture utilizes cross-functional teams. Each team are responsible to make specific products based on one or more individual services.

The real value of microservices is realized when we focus on two key aspects: _speed and safety_. Every single decision you make about your software development ends up as a trade-off that impacts these two ideals. Finding an effective balance between them at scale is what we call the microservices way.

_&quot;Speed and Safety at Scale and in Harmony&quot;._ The Microservices Way(O&#39;Reilly: Building Microservices)

- **Speed of change** : Deploy becomes faster and less traumatic; With smaller components, that communicate with each other, forming a granular application, changes become very easier as the project size is consderable small, it becomes a lot faster to deploy new features, as a microservice unit is self contained and operates isolated from the other, it does not affect the other microservices on the environment, so the responsible team can implement, build and deploy new features on it&#39;s context without having to release every other contexts that currently doesn&#39;t require a new version, accelerating the release phase of the feature.
- **Safety of change** - New features deployment becomes less critical;
- Every change is potentially a breaking change and a system optimized purely for speed is only realistic if the cost of breaking the system is near zero, and with microservices, we can achieve it.
- **At scale** - Attend increased demand when necessary; Microservices units are isolated, so with increased demand on a single feature, it&#39;s possible to scale it isolated, without having to scale the entire environment.
- **In Harmony** - Attend the company necessities; Companies that anchieve sucess with microservices are able to maintain their systems stability while increasing their change velocity, so, in other words, they created a harmony of speed and safety that works for their own context.
